subject: HISTORY
text: Describe briefly how either Scotland or England came to be united under one ruler.

subject: HISTORY
text: Write notes on two of the following: Agricola, Domesday Book, Thomas Becket, Edward I’s Scottish policy, the Scottish parliament in the later Middle Ages, the causes of the Wars of the Roses.

subject: HISTORY
text: Do you consider either Henry VII of England or James IV of Scotland to have been a great king? Give reasons.

subject: HISTORY
text: Trace in outline the main events from the accession of Mary Stewart which led up to the Treaty of Edinburgh. What justification is there for calling that treaty a turning point in Scottish history?

subject: HISTORY
text: Give an account of England’s relations with Spain in the reigns of Mary and Elizabeth Tudor.

subject: HISTORY
text: Describe Charles I’s financial expedients from his accession to the summoning of the Long Parliament. State very briefly any causes of trouble other than financial.

subject: HISTORY
text: Give an account of Cromwell’s domestic policy after the expulsion of the Rump and explain why the Commonwealth came to an end.

text: Trace and explain the events of James II’s reign that led to the Revolution of

subject: HISTORY
text: What were the main achievements in home and foreign affairs of Queen Anne’s reign? Does the reign deserve to be called a glorious one?

subject: HISTORY
text: Give an account of the British and French colonies on the mainland of North America about the year 1750 and show what advantages each side possessed.

subject: HISTORY
text: By what methods did the farmers of either Scotland or England increase production in the eighteenth century?

subject: HISTORY
text: State briefly why Britain and France went to war in

subject: HISTORY
text: What part did Britain play in the war up to 1802?

subject: HISTORY
text: Give reasons why there was a demand for parliamentary reform in the years preceding 1832, and show how far the Reform Act of 1832 met that demand.

subject: HISTORY
text: What were the terms of the Treaty of Paris (1856) and what were the further developments in the Eastern Question up to the Treaty of Berlin?

subject: HISTORY
text: How do you account for the success of the Liberals in the election of 1906? What were their main achievements in home affairs up to 1914?

subject: HISTORY
text: Write notes on two of the following: (1) The causes of Lord Durham’s mission to Canada. (2) The construction of the Canadian Pacific Railway and its importance. (3) The causes of the Great Trek. (4) Paul Kruger.

subject: HISTORY
text: Write notes on two of the following: The effects of the rebellion of 1745 on the Highlands, the Diplomatic Revolution of 1756, James Watt, Robert Owen, Abraham Lincoln, Disraeli’s domestic policy, the Treaty of Versailles (1919).

subject: HISTORY
text: Either: Give an account of the projects for the defence of Western Europe proposed since the second world war. Or: What problems have confronted the British Empire in Africa
